<span id="freeTextContainer13577662264240444284">As someone who really enjoys polemicists, mostly what I see in this review is the bitterness of one who wishes themselves a gatekeeper. There&apos;s plenty</span>
  <span id="freeText13577662264240444284" style="display:none">As someone who really enjoys polemicists, mostly what I see in this review is the bitterness of one who wishes themselves a gatekeeper. There's plenty to discuss about McCarthy -- his style, plotting, characters, etc. He's so unusual in all aspects that I think both adoration and condemnation are interesting to read. And McCarthy does indeed draw the attention of critics who have donated considerable time to the task. But this drips of spite, easily spotted as the review suffers constant intrusions of politics, venomous instead of insightful observations, and similar ancillary navel gazing. Which are strange digressions considering the reviewer is not even familiar with the author's work. Calling McCarthy a Hollywood-writer is wildly missing the mark, as is quoting David Foster Wallace who actually adored McCarthy's books. If you've only read the one book, and are clearly unfamiliar with the author, then perhaps stay away from wider literary commentary and stick to the book itself. <br /><br />I say that as someone who otherwise can see the more basic critiques as fair enough, by the way. That the review proves itself a very suitable totem for those who share similar feelings almost makes me think less of those critiques, though.</span>
